ing. Well - well - well - that's really for the bride because seems to be getting lost. The - the old wife is dead, only me and her knew about that, the old lady is dead now, Mrs - \{BLANK\}
 she's dead, there's only two - well better tell you something about
 the - the early weddings - ceremonies. That's before we come to the wedding I'd better tell you about the custom - called sp spurring for the bride. That was that it was the custom for the young, for the bridegroom elect - to go and ask the father - for 
-
 for - for for the - for the girl, the daughter. There was no bride price you know or anything like that but it was the custom just to go and ask, and it was generally either Saturday night that - that you'd go. And all that he had to take with him was a 
good bottle of scotch whisky. And of course - you know that - most of the marriage was - was done in the wintertime. Was most of it, sort of the heartier time and better for dancing and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16545636\charrsid14301207 
 all that and so they - they mar}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14894142\charrsid14301207 ried mostly in the winter, in - like som
e parts in the south I gathered it - it was - the marriage never done in the month of May, have you heard that? Have you never heard that, oh no, no, no, not in the month of May. And - of course the girl wouldn't know what he was - coming and - likely the
 
old people too but - he would set out - and he would arrive maybe about nine o'clock at the house. And of course he would be welcomed then in the house and - was sitting in called the butt end, and after a time the - wife of the house, the other - man's w
i
fe would go and set about tea, whilst they're all home baking bread you know they would have. That home baking meal, that was called bursting brownies, bursting cakes. And when the table's about to be set in he would - the young man - would - walk - he'll
 go to his coat and take out this bottle of whisky and set it in the middle of the table, and say nothing. And the father would say, now bairns, set you in around. And boy, set thee in among us, and that was the - that showed then - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16545636\charrsid14301207 that he was accepted into the f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14894142\charrsid14301207 amily. That was the words that were spoken.
