 among us. That means he was accepted into the family. And so they would run out this whisky, and they would - drink to the health of this - of this two intended, this couple, wish them all the best and - and then after
 a time, you - you - you make for home. You didna stop long, and that was - that was the spurring night, you'd make for home. Then after that of course was the contract - time, the proclamation, and then - the wedding, sometimes - very often you know the 
w
eddings was held at the ordinary houses. There were no halls in those days so much, it was just in the houses. And one of the rooms - or - or if they had a big barn was cleared out for the dancing. And - all the neighbours would help - in baking bread and
 baking - \{BLANK\}
 cakes was called the bride's bun. That was part of it. And - some of us - when they came from the church to the house they - they would get some of the bride's bun and some of this - oat - oatcakes. And the greeting that's - various things
 to say that seems to be lost too. When - they toasted the guest of that bride and bridegroom was, weel brook thee noo.
